# NickelHintFix

Fixes a vertical "wobble" in Kobo's reader where individual letters drift up/down
by a pixel, on fonts that ship no per-glyph hinting instructions.
When Nickel requests hinted glyph loads, iType grid-fits those raw outlines itself
and snaps the same letter to different pixel heights in different places.

NickelHintFix loads glyphs with FT_LOAD_NO_HINTING so iType draws the raw outline
(as desktop FreeType does for these glyphs) and the line goes flat. iType stays the
renderer.

## Vertical-text fix

It also fixes vertical (tategaki) CJK books rendering wrong when "better typography"
(eReader.conf webkitTextRendering=optimizeLegibility) is on. That setting forces
WebKit's complex text path, which has no vertical-writing-mode support, so the chōonpu
ー, brackets 「」, and punctuation 、。 come out horizontal/mislaid. For vertical views
only, NickelHintFix pushes a user stylesheet (*{text-rendering:auto !important}) onto the
page, which re-renders it on the simple path (the one that renders tategaki correctly).
Horizontal books are untouched and keep "better typography", so your eReader.conf choice
is otherwise respected.

## Preferences (KOBOeReader/.adds/nickelhintfix/config)

- nhf_enabled:1            enable/disable everything; 0 = behaves as if not installed
- nhf_no_hinting:1         load glyphs unhinted (the hinting fix); 0 = stock behaviour
- nhf_hinting_allowlist:   comma-separated families exempt from nhf_no_hinting
- nhf_vertfix:1            fix vertical books under "better typography"; 0 = off
- nhf_vertfix_debug:0      verbose vertical-fix logging (advanced; default off)

Changes take effect on reboot.

## Uninstall

Delete KOBOeReader/.adds/nickelhintfix/uninstall and reboot. The mod never
self-uninstalls on errors (a safety trip writes disabled-by-safety and keeps it
inert until that marker is removed).
